ation, division, and enclosure. Instead, he argues that urban imaginaries can and often do offer visions of more open communities and more inclusive urban futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCity and town lifezArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aCommonszArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aCommunity lifezArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aDictatorshipxSocial aspectszArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aNeoliberalismxSocial aspectszArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aPolitics and culturezArgentinazBuenos Aires. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aSociology : Urban Studies. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438460581423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438460581/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles